Happy #epilepsyawarenessday 💜 I had my first seizure during chemistry class in 10th grade. My teachers words melted into an unrecognizable language as my ears rang. The class bell rang, and I walked down the long, sterile hallway like a drunkard, swaying side to side and running into walls. When I reached my next class, Spanish, I fumbled as I failed to speak full sentences, and a classmate helped escort me to the nurse. As I struggled to speak and regain my motor skills for 2 hours, my mother came to pick me up and drive me to the emergency room. The day I was diagnosed, I was strong in the neurologist’s office, then told my mom I wanted to go back to school, and proceeded to vomit in the bathroom during lunch. I think I was in shock. It has been an ongoing battle for many years, but I am forever grateful for the strength and the skills that my Epilepsy journey has granted me. Thank you @epilepsylosangeles for organizing this walk 💜✨

"I have no idea when my #tick bit me. I never got the famous #Lymedisease rash. I woke up one morning in 10th grade & half of my face was paralyzed. My mother rushed me to the ER thinking I was having a stroke, & it turned out to be Bell’s Palsy. My facial nerves were being attacked due to longterm, untreated Lyme disease. Within the same six months, I had my first seizure & was diagnosed with Epilepsy with cause unknown.
 
Over the next 10 years, I visited primary care doctors, infectious disease specialists, natural paths, & Lyme doctors, just to spend tons of money, be treated with three weeks of antibiotics over & over again, & watch my health decline as my diagnoses increased. I had seizures, fibromyalgia, gastritis, trigeminal neuralgia, pain, fatigue, cognitive decline, muscle spasms, sleep paralysis, vision problems, & depression. The best medicine I found over my 10 years was my learned ability to self-advocate.

Sleeping an average of 14-16 hours per day, I had to let go of the ability to have dreams & set goals. From then on out, the main objective was survival & keeping my head above water. This included sitting down with teachers & bosses, & explaining my situation to them. I had to research myself & my new brain after losing 21 IQ points over night to discover which learning & work methodologies could work for me, & then self-advocate in settings of school & work to find unique ways to get by.

After almost ten years, I began to present early signs of a degenerative disease. I was having muscle spasms, vision problems, and tingling & numbness in my extremities. This was the moment I realized I could not accept my reality as my new normal. I was getting worse, & I had to act fast. So I went back to the drawing board, & finally found a Lyme doctor who was willing to do what it took to get me better. After three months of intensive treatment, I went from having eight strands of Lyme bacterias, to three. While my health is still a journey, & I continue to struggle on the road to finding normalcy & routine within the body that I have, I’m much better off than I was, & I am forever grateful. I’m still fighting, but I’m ok. I’m more than ok." @iammaxnoir

MRIs are a traumatic experience for me. I know it doesn’t sound like a big deal, but for me, there’s an extra layer. They often times trigger a seizure for me. I have to sit in that small small space while a machine screams at me, and I count from 1 to 60, twenty-five times, waiting to see if I seize or not. The nurses implement “seizure protocol”. The stress I experience during this time increases my chances of having a seizure, creating cyclical fear. I celebrate every single quarter minute, half minute, and full minute that goes by as a major milestone in order to get through. Staying still as stone as my brain is in sheer panic and my body in a cold sweat. 

Medical things, no matter how seemingly small, are scary, and I send strength to any of you who have or are enduring conditions 💜 Proud of myself for getting through another one.
Wish you guys knew what I was shooting this content for 😁🌊 All in due time 👀

🎉 It’s my birthday! 🎉 The last year has been the hardest year of my adult life. I lost two jobs, faced heartbreak, ran out of money, had to move back home, and have failed to get a new job. With a long season of stress, depression, imposter syndrome, and uncertainty, I have been able to make out out the other side with a shifted perspective, growth, and a ton of mental clarity. 

I used to chase big pay checks, since I once had them. I thought making less money made me a failure. But while receiving those big paychecks, I was unhappy and unfulfilled. I didn’t care about the work I was doing. I’m happy to finally say I’ve released that need. Now, i am chasing creativity, intention, and bliss. I don’t want to live just to work. How I spend my time is changing greatly, and I look forward to surprising you all, very soon, with Max Season 2. ✨♥️ Big things are coming ☺️
